Given two strings s1 and s2, check if s2 is a permutation of s1. Two strings are permutations of each other if they contain exactly the same characters in the same frequencies, but the order of characters can be different.

Constraints
The length of both strings is between 1 and 100,000.
Both strings consist of lowercase English letters only.
Examples
Input: s1 = "listen", s2 = "silent"

Output: true

Explanation: "silent" is a permutation of "listen" because both strings have the same characters with the same frequencies.

Input: s1 = "triangle", s2 = "integral"

Output: true

Explanation: "integral" is a permutation of "triangle".

Input: s1 = "hello", s2 = "world"
#include <iostream>
#include <string>
using namespace std;

bool areAnagrams(const string& s1, const string& s2) {
    // Check if lengths are different
    if (s1.length() != s2.length()) {
        return false;
    }

    // Array to store character frequencies
    int charCount[26] = {0};

    // Count frequencies for s1 and s2
    for (int i = 0; i < s1.length(); ++i) {
        charCount[s1[i] - 'a']++;
        charCount[s2[i] - 'a']--;
    }

    // Check if all counts are zero
    for (int count : charCount) {
        if (count != 0) {
            return false;
        }
    }

    return true;
}

int main() {
    string s1 = "listen";
    string s2 = "silent";
    cout << "Are the strings anagrams? " << (areAnagrams(s1, s2) ? "true" : "false") << endl;

    s1 = "hello";
    s2 = "world";
    cout << "Are the strings anagrams? " << (areAnagrams(s1, s2) ? "true" : "false") << endl;

    return 0;
}
Output: false

Explanation: "world" is not a permutation of "hello" because the characters do not match.

This problem requires checking whether two given strings are permutations of each other 
by verifying if they have identical character distributions.

